Montpellier Operational Center 371 rue du Pr. J. Blayac 34184 Montpellier Cedex 04 France
TOXICOLOGY STUDY REPORT TSA1482 M000473 -Rifapentine -4-week subchronic oral toxicity study in macaques with a 2-week recovery period
Test Facility: sanofi-aventis recherche & développement Disposition, Safety and Animal Research Study Director: Erik Guillén Product code: M000473 -Rifapentine Total number of pages: 696 + 1 page for Electronic Signatures Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 1 1/700
TABLE OF CONTENTS TOXICOLOGY SUMMARY STUDY NUMBER: TSA1482 TITLE: Rifapentine -4-week subchronic oral toxicity study in macaques with a 2-week recovery period STUDY DIRECTOR: Erik llén The purpose of this study was to determine the potential toxicity of rifapentine when administered once daily to Macaca fascicularis by oral gavage for 4 weeks and to assess reversibility of potential compound effects after 2 weeks. In addition, the systemic exposure to rifapentine was determined and the presence of 25-desacetyl rifapentine metabolite in plasma was investigated after repeated doses. For convenience, "M000473-rifapentine" was named rifapentine throughout the Study Report. Macaca fascicularis (26 to 39 months of age) received 0.5% (w/v) methylcellulose (vehicle control group) or aqueous suspension of rifapentine in vehicle at 80, 160 or 480 mg/kg/day by oral gavage (10 mL/kg) once daily for 4 weeks. There were 3 animals per sex/group, and 2 additional animals per sex in the control and high-dose groups served as recovery animals. Recovery animals were maintained without compound administration for 2 weeks after completion of 4 weeks of dosing. The parameters evaluated included mortality, clinical signs, body weights, food consumption, ophthalmology, electrocardiography, hematology, clinical chemistry, and urinalysis. Plasma samples for toxicokinetic determinations were obtained. The animals were euthanized and necropsied at the end of treatment and at the end of the recovery period. Weights of selected organs were recorded and representative tissue samples were examined microscopically in all the animals sacrificed at the end of the treatment period. Tissues with potential treatment-related findings were also evaluated microscopically for all recovery animals. Electron microscopy examination was also performed on liver of 3 animals per sex from the control and high dose groups sacrificed at the end of the treatment period. Results Toxicokinetic results showed that following a 4-week repeated oral administration at doses of 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day of rifapentine, all macaques were exposed to rifapentine on dosing Days 1 and 29. Concentrations of rifapentine and 25-desacetyl rifapentine were below the lower limit of quantitation (LLOQ, 0.5 µg/mL for both) in all control animals. Whatever the sex, the dose and the toxicokinetic sampling day, rifapentine concentrations were above the LLOQ up to 24 hours in all treated animals. Plasma concentrations of the rifapentine metabolite, 25-desacetyl rifapentine, were all below 0.5 µg/mL or below 2 µg/mL for samples diluted 4-fold. Overall, considering AUC 0-24 ratios between males and females, no obvious sex effect was observed. Rifapentine AUC 0-24 decreased after repeated dose administration indicating a possible autoinduction phenomenon. The exposure decrease after repeated administration was quite similar at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day (about 50%). For the high dose (480 mg/kg/dose) the decrease was lower (below 40%). After administered dose was increased from 80 to 160 mg/kg/day (2-fold increase), in females, the exposure remained almost constant on Day 1 and Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infradose proportionality on Day 1 and remained almost constant on Day 29. After administered dose was increased from 160 to 480 mg/kg/day (3-fold increase), in females, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and on Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and dose-proportionally on Day 29. On completion of the 4-week oral administration of rifapentine to macaques at 80, 160 or 480 mg/kg/day, including a 2-week recovery period at 480 mg/kg/day, the following findings were noted: • Liver: -From 80 mg/kg/day upwards, in some animals, slightly higher ALT activity (mainly at 480 mg/kg/day), slightly low cholesterol (all doses, both sexes) associated in one 480 mg/kg/day treated female with lower triglyceride level and slightly higher total bilirubin in both sexes at 480 mg/kg/day. All these changes were reversible and may be related to the liver changes seen on anatomopathology examination (see below). -Slightly to moderately higher absolute and relative liver mean weights, minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement, and minimal to moderate hypertrophy of hepatocytes from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in both sexes, with slight dose-related effects on weights for males and in both sexes for the other findings. The hypertrophy of hepatocytes concerned centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes in all cases, but also periportal hepatocytes, at lower occurrence and severity degree. In most cases, centrilobular and midzonal hypertrophy was more prominent in subcapsular lobules, where it was associated, at minimal to mild degrees, with large multinucleated syncytial hepatocytes and multifocal necrosis (with/without hemorrhage and/or acute/subacute inflammation), from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, in both sexes and with slight doserelated effects. These findings were considered to result from liver enzyme induction, with possible roles of (i) relative hypoxia, when considering the increased severity noted in subcapsular lobules, (ii) drug class effect and/or increased total bilirubin plasma levels, when considering the syncytial hepatocytes. -A slight increase in hepatocytic neutral fat contents was also noted from 80 and 160 mg/kg/day upwards, in males and females, respectively, slightly dose-related in males. This finding was considered as a most likely adaptative finding, possibly linked with decreases in total cholesterol plasma levels. -Finally, a minimal/mild light pale discoloration was noted in one male and one female at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids, and to the increase in neutral fat contents. Transmission electronic microscopic (TEM) examination, performed in 480 mg/kg/daytreated monkeys killed at the end of the dosing period, confirmed the microscopic findings and showed that the hepatocyte hypertrophy was due to an increase in smooth endoplasmic reticulum (SER) consistent with liver enzyme induction. At 480 mg/kg/day, light pale discoloration, increased weight, hypertrophy of centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes, syncytial hepatocytes, foci of necrosis, and increase in neutral fat contents did not fully reverse. • Adrenals: -Minimal to moderate hypertrophy of zona fasciculata cells, with more or less correlative decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia, was noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 80 and 480 mg/kg/day, these findings correlated with slightly higher absolute and/or relative weights and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in some macaques. In the absence of any stress-related findings in the study, these findings were considered as a most likely adaptative response, possibly linked to the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels. At 480 mg/kg/day, the increase in weight, and the decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia of zona fasciculata cells had almost fully reversed. • Digestive tube -Red vomiting and/or regurgitation with no clear dose-relationship, and dose-related dark red feces were seen from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in males and from 160 mg/kg/day upwards in females. The red discoloration of vomit or feces was attributed to the coloration of rifapentine, and was considered as non adverse. -Slight body weight loss in two males treated at 480 mg/kg/day probably secondary to the vomiting presented by these two animals. -Non adverse minimal/mild dark or orange discoloration of the stomachal, duodenal, jejunal, ileal and/or cecal mucosa from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, dose-related but not sex-related, and attributed to the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues. -Minimal increase in incidence or severity of lacteal duct distension was noted in the ileum from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 480 mg/kg/day, this finding was associated with minimal to moderate lacteal duct ending cysts, filled with neutral fat, in the duodenum or jejunum from all males and one female, and with minimal increase in macrophagic infiltration of jejunal and ileal villi in one male (with increase in cytoplasmic eosinophilia). A possible link of these findings with the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels may be evoked. At 480 mg/kg/day, dark or orange discoloration did not fully reverse, and the lacteal duct endings cysts did not reverse. In addition, morphologically similar cysts were noted in the mesenteric lymph nodes sinuses of one 480 mg/kg/day treated female killed at the end of the recovery period. • Spleen and lymph nodes: -Mild to moderate increase (in frequency and distribution, but not in severity) in lymphoid follicular hyperplasia from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sexrelated effects. In the spleen, the finding correlated with slightly to moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, dose-related in males, and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in one female at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day. This finding, not fully reversible at 480 mg/kg/day, was attributed to a stimulating effect on lymphoid follicles, ie, on the immune system B cell compartment. At 480 mg/kg/day, increase in follicular hyperplasia did not fully reverse in lymph nodes. • Kidneys: -Blood in urine was observed from 80 mg/kg/day in both sexes without histopathology correlate. At 480 mg/kg/day, higher urobilinogen in two females associated with orange urine discoloration in one female was also observed. -Light pale discoloration was noted in one female at 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids. This finding was still noted in one female at the end of the recovery period. In addition, minor findings were noted, the final attribution of which to rifapentine remains questionable. Some may have participated to a more generalized effect on the lymphoid system: hyperplastic lymphoid follicle in the thymus from one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, and slightly higher incidence and/or severity of (i) multifocal lymphoid lymphocytic infiltration in the sublingual and lacrymal glands and prostate (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), mandibular gland (from 160 mg/kg/day), and ciliary body (at 480 mg/kg/day), (ii) multifocal and most likely inflammatory lymphocytic infiltration in stomachal neural plexuses (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and (iii) multifocal perivascular/vascular chronic inflammation in brain (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), epididymis, skeletal muscle and sciatic nerve (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and testis and cervix (at 480 mg/kg/day). At the end of the recovery period (480 mg/kg/day), only the increase in multifocal lymphocytic infiltration was still noted in neural plexuses and lacrymal gland. Therefore, under these study conditions, 160 mg/kg/day was considered as No-ObservedAdverse-Effect-Level (NOAEL) since changes seen at these doses remained mostly minimal or slight, were adaptative in nature and were demonstrated to be reversible or partially reversible at 480 mg/kg/day. The dose of 480 mg/kg/day was considered as potentially adverse in view of the increased intensity of the changes and of the non reversible character of the lacteal duct ending cysts in the digestive tube. At 160 mg/kg/day, C max was 29.8 ± 7.15 µg/mL in males and 30.8 ± 13.2 µg/mL in females and AUC 0-24 386 ± 55.3 µg.h/mL in males and 438 ± 209 µg.h/mL in females on Day 29. RESPONSIBLE PERSONNEL AT TEST SITE This study is a multisite study; information regarding the Principal Investigator and relevant study phase is given below. Principal Investigator name and OBJECTIVES The purpose of this study was to determine the potential toxicity of rifapentine when administered once daily to Macaca fascicularis by oral gavage for 4 weeks and to assess the reversibility of potential compound effects after 2 weeks. In addition, the systemic exposure of rifapentine (and metabolite 25-desacetyl-rifapentine) was determined. In a previous study (DIV1437 (1) ), 25-desacetyl rifapentine was not found circulating in plasma monkeys after a single oral dose of rifapentine up to 1000 mg/kg. In this study, the presence of this metabolite in plasma was investigated after repeated doses. Rifapentine is an anti-tuberculosis drug currently under development by sanofi-aventis. For convenience, "M000473-rifapentine" is named rifapentine throughout the Study Report. RELEVANT GUIDELINES This study was performed in compliance with the following guidelines or recommendations: • International Conference on Harmonization (ICH) Guideline on non-clinical safety studies for the conduct of human clinical trials and marketing authorization for pharmaceuticals M3(R2) Step 4 version dated June 2009. • International Conference on Harmonization (ICH) Guideline on toxicokinetics: a guidance for assessing systemic exposure in toxicology studies, S3A, Step 5 version, dated June 1995. • EEC guidelines: 75/318/CEE and the rules governing medical products in the European Union, January 1996. • Guidance on Repeated Dose Toxicity EMEA/CHMP/SWP/488313/2007 dated February 2008. The sampling and analysis dates as well as the results of these analyses are detailed in the Analytical Phase Report presented in ~xr2i . Dose levels Dose levels and concentrations are expressed as active ingredient of test article. Rationale for dose selection The dose levels were based on the results of a 1-month study (CIT/Study No. 36242 TSP (2) ) conducted in macaques where doses of 20, 40 and 80 mg/kg/day of rifapentine were tested. • In this study, at 80 mg/kg/day, no signs of systemic toxicity were observed at clinical examination during both the treatment and treatment-free periods. At the end of the treatment period, changes in blood biochemistry were limited to statistically significantly decreased cholesterol level that was reversible on completion of the treatment-free period. • At 20 and 40 mg/kg/day, no signs of systemic toxicity were observed at clinical examination during both the treatment and treatment-free periods. At the end of the treatment period, changes in blood biochemistry were limited to a decrease in cholesterol level, which was of low magnitude, with values remaining close to physiological values and therefore not considered to be adverse. There were dose-related trends towards increased liver weights in males and females at all doses. A relationship to treatment was considered to be possible but of minor toxicological importance as these weight differences were minimal and did not correlate with macroscopic or microscopic Exceptions • on the days of ophthalmology examinations, the animals received food in the afternoon after waking up from anesthesia. Food was removed at least 4 hours after distribution with few exceptions where food was available only for 3 hours, documented in the study data; • on the days of sampling for hematology, coagulation, blood chemistry or urinalysis, the animals were sampled before food distribution on that day (they are fastened overnight). Food was distributed following the scheme described before during the acclimatization, treatment and recovery periods. In all cases, food consumption was estimated since animals had food at their disposition for at least 4 hours per day. In addition to the pelleted diet, animals received a piece of dried fruit/or vegetable per day and, and as reward after treatment, they received a piece of dried fruit or ginger bread. Water: Free access to controlled tap water through automatic waterers (or bottles). Feed and water enrichment analysis: Feed and water were analyzed periodically to ensure that contaminants known to be capable of interfering with the study and reasonably expected to be present were not detected at levels considered capable of affecting the toxicity of the test article or otherwise influence the outcome of the study. Diet and water analyses were satisfactory and all analysis results are retained in the Test Facility archives. Acclimatization: For at least 3 weeks. All the animals received gavage administration of 20 mL per day of tap water during the week preceding the beginning of treatment (from Day -7 onwards) to minimize stress on the first days of treatment. Randomization procedure Animals were assigned to dosage groups based on computerized randomization. a The first two males and females in control and high-dose groups were kept for recovery Number of animals/group Method: The ophthalmology examination was performed in the morning (in the dosing phase just after treatment). On the examination days, food was distributed after ophthalmologic examination (after waking up from anesthesia) (see Section 5.2.2.2). • Mydriatic eye drops, Atropine 0.5% (Alcon atropine), instilled prior to examination of the eyes. • Then animals were anesthetized with ketamine hydrochloride, 10 mg/kg, I.M. (Imalgène 500, Mérial). The examination of the intraocular structures and fundus was made with a Welch Allyn binocular indirect ophthalmoscope and a portable slit lamp (Kowa SL-15). Control sample tubes were stored in a separate container from the other dosed groups to minimize the potential for cross-contamination of control samples. Concentrations of rifapentine and 25-desacetyl rifapentine in plasma samples were determined using a HPLC/UV method previously validated by the Test Site. A Bioanalytical Phase Report was issued: results were provided as tables including individual concentrations, standard calibration curves and quality controls (see ~xr3i ). Toxicokinetic evaluation Toxicokinetic analysis was only performed for rifapentine since almost all concentrations from treated macaques (262 out of 264 specimens) were below the lower limit of quantitation for 25-desacetyl rifapentine (0.5 µg/mL) or below 2.0 µg/mL for sample diluted 4-fold (see Toxicokinetic Evaluation Phase Report in ~xr4i ). Toxicokinetic evaluation: Statistical and toxicokinetic evaluation of the determined concentrations was made using an EXCEL spreadsheet program and /or WinNonLin Software. Arithmetic mean, standard deviation (SD), coefficient of variation (CV%), median, min, max as function of parameters were calculated on plasma concentrations for each sampling timepoint per treatment group and gender. As no modifications were seen, the examination of low and mid-dose group smears was not considered necessary by the Study Director. Approximately 2 mL of serum were collected into dry tubes and stored at approximately -80°C for potential biomarker analysis. Appendix V DATA COLLECTION AND ANALYSIS SYSTEMS Data were recorded directly using appropriate laboratory forms or by computer entry. The instruments and systems used for data collection, data analysis and reporting were the following: Type STATISTICAL METHODS Dosing Phase data for each dose group were reported using descriptive statistics for specified time points. For body weight and body weight change values, the statistical evaluation was based on the assumption of a monotonic dose-response relationship. A step-down trend test procedure was applied, using all doses to determine the dose level at which there is no statistical significance of trend for each parameter. Statistical evaluations over the low dose group(s) were only carried out if significant effects were detected in the higher dose group(s). The first step included all doses and was conducted two-sided, and allowed assessment of the direction of the trend (up or down); when significance was found, the highest dose group was excluded and a one-sided trend test based on the determined test direction was repeated for the remaining groups, until no significant effect could be found. For all the other parameters as there were less than 4 quantifiable values in low and mid-dose groups, no statistical analysis was performed, and the data were reported using descriptive statistics only. For animals euthanized at the end of the Dosing Phase, organ weights and final body weights were analyzed for statistical significance (p ≤ 0.05) by the two-sided Dunnett test. Statistical analyses were not performed in the Pretest Phase and Recovery Phase. RESULTS AND DISCUSSION TOXICOKINETICS The Bioanalytical Phase Report is presented in ~xr7i and the Toxicokinetic Evaluation Phase Report in ~xr8i . Toxicokinetic profile Toxicokinetic results showed that following a 4-week repeated oral administration at doses of 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day of rifapentine, all macaques were exposed to rifapentine on dosing Days 1 and 29. Concentrations of rifapentine and 25-desacetyl rifapentine were below the lower limit of quantitation (LLOQ, 0.5 µg/mL for both) in all control animals. Whatever the sex, the dose and the toxicokinetic sampling day, rifapentine concentrations were above the LLOQ up to 24 hours in all treated animals. Plasma concentrations of the rifapentine metabolite, 25-desacetyl rifapentine, were all below 0.5 µg/mL or below 2 µg/mL for samples diluted 4-fold. Sex effect Overall, considering AUC 0-24 ratios between males and females, no obvious sex effect was observed. Multiple dosing effect Rifapentine AUC 0-24 decreased after repeated dose administration indicating a possible autoinduction phenomenon. The exposure decrease after repeated administration was quite similar at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day (about 50%). For the high dose (480 mg/kg/day) the decrease was lower (below 40%). Dose proportionality After administered dose was increased from 80 to 160 mg/kg/day (2-fold increase), in females, the exposure remained almost constant on Day 1 and Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infradose proportionality on Day 1 and remained almost constant on Day 29. After administered dose was increased from 160 to 480 mg/kg/day (3-fold increase), in females, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and on Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and dose-proportionally on Day 29. The toxicokinetic parameters of rifapentine are summarized in Text Table 1 . Almost all plasma concentrations of 25-desacetyl rifapentine being below the lower limit of quantitation, no toxicokinetic parameters were determined for the metabolite. Mean ± SD (CV%) Values rounded to 3 significant figures with the exception of CV that was rounded to 2 significant figures. Appendix III Appendix IV Text IN-LIFE OBSERVATIONS Mortality No mortality was recorded (see ~xr9i and ~xr10i ). Clinical signs Clinical signs are summarized in ~xr11i and individual data are presented in ~xr12i . Compound-related clinical signs are presented in Text Table 2 . Text Table 2 Table 1 Table 12 Table 2 Table 13 The red discoloration of vomit or feces (dose-related) was attributed to the coloration of rifapentine. Animal 13M (80 mg/kg/day) was very sensible to the gavage procedure and often regurgitated. The vomiting/regurgitation had no clear dose-relationship. All of these signs were not seen during the recovery period. The other clinical signs were considered as incidental (wound on hind limb or tail). Body weight Group mean values are presented in ~xr13i and ~xr14i and ~xr15i , individual data are presented in ~xr16i and ~xr17i . No compound-related body weight changes were observed at 80 or 160 mg/kg/day. The slight body weight loss observed in two high-dose (480 mg/kg/day) treated males (26M and 27M) during the first week of treatment, leading to a statistically significant decrease in mean body weight gain, may be related to the vomits that these two animals presented mainly during the first week of treatment. The few mean body weight variations noted between Day 29 and Day 31 were attributed to the euthanasia of monkeys among the more light or heavy animals, at the scheduled end-treatment necropsy. The other statistically significant variations on body weight or body weight changes were not considered as compound-related. Food consumption Group mean values are presented in ~xr18i and ~xr19i , and individual data are presented in ~xr20i . No treatment-related changes in food consumption were observed. At 480 mg/kg/day, some females (29F, 31F and 32 F) sporadically presented decreased food consumption during the study, but this was considered as spontaneous changes occasionally observed in the monkey. Ophthalmology Individual ophthalmology data are presented in ~xr21i . Ophthalmology examination did not reveal any abnormality. CLINICAL PATHOLOGY In a few instances (eg, clotted sample), the number of values did not correspond to the number of blood samples collected. The number of missing values did not compromise the validity of the study. All the results are expressed as compared to mean control values (percent change as compared to mean control values). Hematology Group mean values are presented in ~xr26i , and individual data are presented in ~xr27i . No treatment-related changes were observed. All observed mean and individual changes were interpreted to be spontaneous variations without toxicological significance, or to be within the expected physiological variations as remaining within or close to the control or pretreatment values, and/or without correlation with relevant histopathological changes, in particular: • low neutrophil level in one female (29F) treated at 480 mg/kg/day on Day 30. Coagulation Group mean values are presented in ~xr28i , and individual data are presented in ~xr29i . No treatment-related changes were observed. The slightly lower fibrinogen level when compared to control values observed in females 28F, 30F and 31F treated at 480 mg/kg/day was interpreted to be within expected biological variation and not related to treatment with the test article. Clinical chemistry Group mean values are presented in ~xr31i , and individual data are presented in ~xr32i . • Slightly higher ALT activity (2-to 3-fold when compared with pre-test values) was observed mainly in 12M (80 mg/kg/day), 23M, 24M, 25M, 29F and 31F (480 mg/kg/day) at the end of treatment with very slightly higher mean ALT activity in males at all doses and females at 480 mg/kg/day. This change was no more seen in the two high-dose animals kept for recovery (24M and 29F); • Higher total bilirubin level in animals 24M, 27M and 29F at 480 mg/kg/day resulting in higher mean total bilirubin level in both sexes (+77% in males and +175% in females when compared to control mean) at the end of treatment. This change was no more seen in the two high-dose animals kept for recovery (24M and 29F); • Slightly lower plasma cholesterol was observed at all doses in males (-51%, -64% and -60% at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, respectively) and females (-35%, -40% and -58% at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, respectively) associated at 480 mg/kg/day with a slightly lower triglyceride level in one female (29F). All these changes were not more seen at the end of the recovery period. Other differences in mean or individual clinical chemistry values when compared to controls recorded in the tables (mainly higher glucose level in one female treated at 80 mg/kg/day and in females treated at 480 mg/kg/day) were interpreted to be within expected biological variation and not related to treatment with the test article. In addition, the higher direct bilirubin levels observed were due to method interference due to the orange discoloration of rifapentine. Urinalysis Group mean values are presented in ~xr33i , and individual data are presented in ~xr34i and ~xr35i . The following compound-related change was observed: • Red (20F, 160 mg/kg/day) or orange (29F, 480 mg/kg/day) discoloration of urine in two females; • Blood in urine was detected from 80 mg/kg/day in both sexes; • Higher urobilinogen in two 480 mg/kg/day treated females (29F and 30F). The presence of glucose detected in urine of 29F is due to method interference related to the orange discoloration of the sample provoked by the orange discoloration of rifapentine. Table 22 Table 10 Table 23 Table 11 Table 24 Table 25 A slight increase in hepatocytic neutral fat contents was also noted from 80 and 160 mg/kg/day upwards, in males and females respectively, slightly dose-related in males. This finding was considered as a most likely adaptative finding, possibly linked with decreases in total cholesterol plasma levels. Finally, a minimal/mild light pale discoloration was noted in one male and one female at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids, and to the increase in neutral fat contents. Transmission electron microscopic (TEM) examination, performed in 480 mg/kg/day-treated monkeys killed at the end of the dosing period, confirmed the microscopic findings, and showed that the hepatocyte hypertrophy was due to an increase in smooth endoplasmic reticulum (SER), consistent with liver enzyme induction. At 480 mg/kg/day, light pale discoloration, increased weight, hypertrophy of centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes, syncytial hepatocytes, foci of necrosis, and increase in neutral fat contents did not fully reverse. In the adrenals, minimal to moderate hypertrophy of zona fasciculata cells, with more or less correlative decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia, was noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 80 and 480 mg/kg/day, these findings correlated with slightly higher absolute and/or relative weights and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in some macaques. In the absence of any stress-related findings in the study, these findings were considered as a most likely adaptative response, possibly linked to the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels. At 480 mg/kg/day, the increase in weight, and the decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia of zona fasciculata cells had almost fully reversed. In the digestive tube, a minimal increase in incidence or severity of lacteal duct distension was noted in the ileum from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 480 mg/kg/day, this finding was associated with minimal to moderate lacteal duct ending cysts, filled with neutral fat, in the duodenum or jejunum from all males and one female, and with minimal increase in macrophagic infiltration of jejunal and ileal villi in one male (with increase in cytoplasmic eosinophilia). A possible link of these findings with the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels may be evoked. Minimal/mild dark or orange discoloration of the stomachal, duodenal, jejunal, ileal and/or cecal mucosa was also noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, with relation to dose but without relation to sex, and was attributed to the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids. At 480 mg/kg/day, dark or orange discoloration did not fully reverse, and the lacteal duct endings cysts did not reverse, in addition, morphologically similar cysts were noted in the mesenteric lymph nodes sinuses of one female. In spleen and lymph nodes, a mild to moderate increase in lymphoid follicles hyperplasia was noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. In the spleen the finding correlated with slightly higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, dose-related in males, and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in one female at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day. This finding was attributed to a stimulating effect on lymphoid follicles, ie, on the immune system B cell compartment. At 480 mg/kg/day, the increase in follicular hyperplasia did not fully reverse in lymph nodes. In kidneys, light pale discoloration was noted in one female at 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids. This finding was still noted in one female at the end of the recovery period. In addition minor findings were noted, the final attribution of which to rifapentine remains questionable. Some may have participated to a more generalized effect on the lymphoid system: hyperplastic lymphoid follicle in the thymus from one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, and slightly higher incidence and/or severity of (i) multifocal lymphoid lymphocytic infiltration in the sublingual and lacrymal glands and prostate (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), mandibular gland (from 160 mg/kg/day), and ciliary body (at 480 mg/kg/day), (ii) multifocal and most likely inflammatory lymphocytic infiltration in stomachal neural plexuses (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and (iii) multifocal perivascular/vascular chronic inflammation in brain (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), epididymis, skeletal muscle and sciatic nerve (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and testis and cervix (at 480 mg/kg/day). At the end of the recovery period (480 mg/kg/day), only the increase in multifocal lymphocytic infiltration was still noted in neural plexuses and lacrymal gland. The other questionable findings were of poor biological (and toxicological) relevance: minimal macrovacuolation of zona reticularis cells in the adrenals from one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, focal adrenocortical hemorrhage in one macaque at 480 mg/kg/day, and non steatotic vacuolation of renal proximal tubular cells in one macaque at 480 mg/kg/day. ENZYME INDUCTION The effects of rifapentine on the regulation of various cyp isoforms (expressed as the expression level of investigated gene), relative to the control (vehicle-treated animals) in monkey livers following a 4-week repeated oral gavage of rifapentine at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day were as follows: • No or only a very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels of cyp1a1 genes; • No or only a very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels of cyp2e1 genes; • Weak (males) to intermediary (top dose in females) mean increases in the expression levels of cyp2a24; • Weak (all doses in males) to intermediary (top dose in females) mean increase in the expression levels of cyp3a5; • High (top dose in males) to intermediary (low and top doses in females) mean increases in the expression levels of cyp3a8. Most "female/male" mRNA expression increases ratio did not suggest any major gender differences in the effect of rifapentine on cyp mRNA expression in monkeys. CONCLUSION The repeated oral administration of rifapentine for 4 weeks to macaques at doses of 80, 160 or 480 mg/kg/day resulted in the following: • Liver: From 80 mg/kg/day upwards, in some animals, slightly higher ALT activity (mainly at 480 mg/kg/day), slightly low cholesterol (all doses, both sexes) associated in one 480 mg/kg/day treated female with lower triglyceride level and slightly higher total bilirubin in both sexes at 480 mg/kg/day. All these changes were reversible and may be related to the liver changes seen on anatomopathology examination (slightly to moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights, minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement, and minimal to moderate hypertrophy of centrilobular to periportal hepatocytes associated in subcapsular lobules with large multinucleated syncytial hepatocytes and multifocal necrosis from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in both sexes; slight increase in hepatocytic neutral fat contents, from 80 and 160 mg/kg/day upwards, in males and females respectively. TEM examination showed that the hepatocyte hypertrophy was due to an increase in SER consistent with liver enzyme induction. At 480 mg/kg/day, light pale discoloration, increased weight, hypertrophy of centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes, syncytial hepatocytes, foci of necrosis, and increase in neutral fat contents did not fully reverse. • Adrenals: Minimal to moderate hypertrophy of zona fasciculata cells, with more or less correlative decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia, from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, sometimes correlated with slightly higher absolute and/or relative weights and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in some macaques. These findings were considered as a most likely adaptative response. At 480 mg/kg/day, increase in weight, decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia of zona fasciculata cells had almost fully reversed. • Digestive tube Red vomiting and/or regurgitation (associated in two males treated at 480 mg/kg/day with body weight loss), and dark red feces were seen from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in males and from 160 mg/kg/day upwards in females. The red or mild dark orange discoloration of vomit, feces and stomachal, duodenal, jejunal, ileal and/or cecal mucosa was attributed to the coloration of rifapentine, and was considered as no-adverse. Minimal increase in incidence or severity of lacteal duct distension was noted in the ileum from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 480 mg/kg/day, this finding was associated with minimal to moderate lacteal duct ending cysts, filled with neutral fat, in the duodenum or jejunum from all males and one female, and with minimal increase in macrophagic infiltration of jejunal and ileal villi in one male (with increase in cytoplasmic eosinophilia). A possible link of these findings with the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels may be evoked. At 480 mg/kg/day, lacteal duct distension had fully reversed but not the ending cysts. Morphologically similar cysts were noted in the mesenteric lymph nodes sinuses of one 480 mg/kg/day treated female killed at the end of the recovery period. • Spleen and lymph nodes: Mild to moderate increase (in frequency and distribution, but not in severity) in lymphoid follicular hyperplasia from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, correlated in spleen with slightly to moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, doserelated in males, and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in one female at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day. This finding, not fully reversible at 480 mg/kg/day, was attributed to a stimulating effect on lymphoid follicles. • Kidneys: Blood in urine was observed from 80 mg/kg/day in both sexes without histopathology correlate. At 480 mg/kg/day, non-adverse orange urine discoloration in one female, higher urobilinogen in two females and light pale discoloration of the kidney in one female killed at the end of the treatment period and another one killed at the end of the recovery period was also observed. In addition, minor findings were noted, the final attribution of which to rifapentine remains questionable. Some may have participated to a more generalized effect on the lymphoid system: hyperplastic lymphoid follicle in the thymus, and slightly higher incidence and/or severity of (i) multifocal lymphoid lymphocytic infiltration in the sublingual and lacrymal glands and prostate, mandibular gland, and ciliary body, (ii) multifocal and most likely inflammatory lymphocytic infiltration in stomachal neural plexuses, and (iii) multifocal perivascular/vascular chronic inflammation in brain, epididymis, skeletal muscle, sciatic nerve, testis and cervix. At the end of the recovery period, only the increase in multifocal lymphocytic infiltration was still noted in neural plexuses and lacrymal gland. Therefore, under these study conditions, 160 mg/kg/day was considered as No-ObservedAdverse-Effect-Level (NOAEL) since changes seen at these doses remained mostly minimal or slight, were adaptative in nature and were demonstrated to be reversible or partially reversible at 480 mg/kg/day. The dose of 480 mg/kg/day was considered as potentially adverse in view of the increased intensity of the changes and of the non reversible character of the lacteal duct ending cysts in the digestive tube. At 160 mg/kg/day, Cmax was 29.8 ± 7.15 µg/mL in males and 30.8 ± 13.2 µg/mL in females and AUC 0-24 386 ± 55.3 µg.h/mL in males and 438 ± 209 µg.h/mL in females on Day 29. study was to determine the concentrations of the test article in the vehicle (also named negative control article). TEST ARTICLE Rifapentine, Batch AN065957, purity correction considered as 100%, ratio salt/base not applicable Total correction/conversion factor : 100% Results of analysis: 15483/BR (dated August 9 th , 2010) Retest date: April 1 st , 2012 FORMULATION Suspensions in 0.5 % (w/v) methylcellulose in purified water Concentration range prepared: 8 to 48 mg/mL. RELEVANT DATES OF THE STUDY PHASE: Start of experimentation (concentration analysis phase): July 6 A gradient reversed phase UPLC method with UV detection was used. The chromatographic system (Waters Acquity) was composed of a pumping system, an auto sampler set at 5°C and a UV detector set at 235 nm. Data were acquired and processed using the software Empower version 2, Build 2154. Column: Acquity BEH C8 (Waters); length: 100 mm; internal diameter: 2.1 mm; particle size: 1.7 µm, operating at room temperature. Mobile phase (flow rate: 0.3 mL/min): Calibration was performed versus a one-point standard at 0.01 mg/mL in water / methanol 50/50 (v/v). o Injection volume: 10 µL. The following suitability tests were performed: specificity, retention times, sensitivity and precision. After sonication, the volume was made up with the same solvent and the resulting solution was homogenized. It was then diluted 1/10 with water / methanol 50/50 (v/v) and homogenized. Suspension at 16 mg/mL: about 1 mL (about 1 g) was transferred in a 200 mL amber volumetric flask. 150 mL of water / methanol 50/50 (v/v) were added to dissolve rifapentine. After sonication, the volume was made up with the same solvent and the resulting solution was homogenized. It was then diluted 1/10 with water / methanol 50/50 (v/v) and homogenized. Suspension at 48 mg/mL: about 1 mL (about 1 g) was transferred in a 200 mL amber volumetric flask. 150 mL of water / methanol 50/50 (v/v) were added to dissolve rifapentine. After sonication, the volume was made up with the same solvent and the resulting solution was homogenized. It was then diluted 1/25 with water / methanol 50/50 (v/v) and homogenized. Vehicle: about 1 mL (about 1 g) was transferred in a 10 mL amber volumetric flask. The volume was made up with water / methanol 50/50 (v/v) and the resulting solution was homogenized. The chromatographic conditions used were as specified in the analysis method. The retention time of the analyte peak provided confirmation of the correct peak identity by comparison with the peak retention time of the standard solution. DEVIATIONS There was no deviation to the analytical method that could impact the quality of the results. - - QUA-MP-2011-22689 EN 1.0 Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 247 247/700 ANALYTICAL REPORT M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 7 RESULTS DATA Samples series 1 The suspensions were manufactured by DSAR formulation laboratory on July 5 th , 2011. Samples from these suspensions and from the vehicle were taken by the Animal Study Conduct Team, on July 6 th , 2011 and provided to the analytical laboratory on the same day. They were assayed on July 6 th , 2011 (analysis reference: 4874ET). The results, expressed as Rifapentine, are gathered in Table 1 . The result at 8 mg/mL after administration did not comply with the acceptance criteria (85.0 to 115.0% of the nominal concentration). A new analysis on the intermediate solution confirmed the result (5.58 mg/mL). The Study Director requested an additional analysis on suspension at 8 mg/mL administered on July 7 th , 2011 (see results section 3.1.2) Samples series 2 The suspensions were manufactured by DSAR formulation laboratory on July 5 th , 2011. Samples from the suspensions at 8 mg/mL were taken by the Animal Study Conduct Team, on July 7 th , 2011 and provided to the analytical laboratory on the same day. - - QUA-MP-2011-22689 EN 1.0 Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 248 248/700 ANALYTICAL REPORT M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 8 They were assayed on July 7 th , 2011 (analysis reference: 4875ET). But an additional analysis of the suspension at 8 mg/mL, before and after administration (series 2), showed that the preparation complied with the acceptance criteria, 85.0 -115.0 % of the nominal concentration. For series 3, all the prepared formulations of Rifapentine in methylcellulose 0.5 % were within the limits specified, 85.0 -115.0 % of the nominal concentrations. Also, it was confirmed that Rifapentine was absent from the vehicle samples. This assay was previously validated [5] . The concentration data were generated from seven runs that fulfilled the acceptance criteria. Sample receipt and storage handling A total of 304 samples arrived deep-frozen at Atlanbio on dry ice, in good conditions and properly labeled. Samples were verified upon arrival. Until analysis, samples were stored in a freezer at approximately -80°C. Acceptance criteria Acceptance criteria were as described in Atlanbio bioanalytical study plan ATL-11-0658 enclosed in Appendix IX. Data management Analysis summary A total of 304 plasma samples were analyzed in seven accepted analytical runs. Almost all plasma concentrations of 25-desacetyl rifapentine being below the lower limit of quantitation, no toxicokinetic parameters were determined for the metabolite. Conclusion Toxicokinetic results showed that following a 4-week repeated oral administration at doses of 80 to 480 mg/kg/day of rifapentine, all macaques were exposed to rifapentine on dosing Days 1 and 29. Concentrations of rifapentine and 25-desacetyl rifapentine were below the lower limit of quantitation (LLOQ, 0.5 µg/mL for both) in all control animals. Whatever the sex, the dose and the toxicokinetic sampling day, rifapentine concentrations were above the LLOQ up to 24 hours in all treated animals. Plasma concentrations of the rifapentine metabolite, 25-desacetyl rifapentine, were all below 0.5 µg/mL or below 2 µg/mL for samples diluted 4-fold. Overall, considering AUC 0-24 ratios between males and females, no obvious sex effect was observed. Rifapentine AUC 0-24 decreased after repeated dose administration indicating a possible autoinduction phenomenon. The exposure decrease after repeated administration was quite similar at Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 336 336/700 Phase Report Toxicokinetics -TSA1482 -TK M000473 -Rifapentine Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 8 80 and 160 mg/kg/day (about 50 %). For the high dose (480 mg/kg/dose) the decrease was lower (below 40%). After administered dose was increased from 80 to 160 mg/kg/day (2-fold increase), in females, the exposure remained almost constant on Day 1 and Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infradose proportionality on Day 1 and remained almost constant on Day 29. After administered dose was increased from 160 to 480 mg/kg/day (3-fold increase), in females, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and on Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and dose proportionality on Day 29. STUDY DESIGN The complete study description is detailed in the full study report and only relevant information related to this study phase is summarized hereafter. Test compound • Compound identification: rifapentine (also identified as M000473). • Test article description: Red to orange crystalline powder • Batch/Lot No.: AN065957 • Administered formulations: Suspension between 8 and 48 mg/mL in 0.5% (w/v) methylcellulose Test system • Animal species/breed/sex: Monkey/Macaque/males and females. • Route of administration: Oral gavage. • Dosing regimen and treatment duration: Once a day for 4 weeks Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 339 339/700 Phase Report Toxicokinetics -TSA1482 -TK M000473 -Rifapentine Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 11 Animals were assigned to dose groups as shown in the Table 1 . Toxicokinetic blood samples All sample collections and sample processing were carried out according to the study plan. Blood samples were collected on the scheduled time points (0.5, 1, 2, 4, 8 and 24 hours post-dosing for treated groups and 4 and 24 hours for control group) on dosing Days 1 and 29, from each animal (3 or 5/sex/group) and transferred in lithium heparin tubes (placed on ice). After collection, blood was centrifuged at approximately 2000 g, for 10 minutes at +4°C. Plasma samples obtained were transferred into 2 labeled polypropylene tubes and stored at approximately -80°C. Bioanalytical method The analysis of rifapentine and its metabolite 25-desacetyl rifapentine in plasma was performed using a validated Liquid chromatography coupled UV detection (LC-UV) assay method (Antlanbio, Saint-Nazaire, France). The lower limit of quantitation (LLOQ) was 0.5 µg/mL for both rifapentine and 25-desacteyl rifapentine. Details of the assay method and bioanalytical results for this study are presented in the Bionalytical Phase Report. Toxicokinetic evaluation Toxicokinetic analysis was only performed for rifapentine since almost all concentrations from treated macaques (262 out of 264 specimens) were below the lower limit of quantitation for 25-desacetyl rifapentine (0.5 µg/mL) or below 2.0 µg/mL for sample diluted 4-fold. So, the following toxicokinetic evaluation method only refers to rifapentine. Concentrations less than the LLOQ (0.5 µg/mL) were taken as equal to zero for PK analysis and for means concentration calculations. For each macaque, the predose value was taken as 0 on Day 1 and taken as equivalent to the 24 th hour concentration for Day 29 assuming that steady-state was achieved. Nominal relative times versus administration were used for toxicokinetic calculations except for 31 specimens out of 304 whose collection time was different by more than 15% from theoretical time. The following toxicokinetic parameters were calculated for each individual animal using a noncompartmental approach: • C max : maximum observed concentration, • t max : time of maximum observed concentration, • AUC 0-24 : area under the plasma concentration-time curve calculated by the linear trapezoidal method from time 0 to 24 hours, • Dose proportionality ratios: ratios of C max and AUC 0-24 versus dose ratio, • Ratio of AUC 0-24 on dosing Day 29 versus AUC 0-24 on dosing Day 1 (accumulation ratio), • Sex ratios (AUC 0-24 in females / AUC 0-24 in males). Descriptive statistics of toxicokinetic parameters (arithmetic mean, SD, CV, median, min, max as function of parameters) were determined for each dose, sex and day. Sex ratio (AUC 0-24 females/males ratios) and dose proportionality (C max and AUC 0-24 ) were calculated using Microsoft Excel 2003. Accumulation ratios (AUC 0-24 on Day 29 versus AUC 0-24 on Day 1) were calculated for each animal and the descriptive statistics of ratios were determined for each dose and sex using WinNonLin. Mean toxicokinetic parameters were determined from full precision individual parameters. Full precision mean pharmacokinetic parameters were used for ratio determination. Finally, in the toxicokinetic phase report: • plasma concentrations and their descriptive statistics (given in Section 11) as well as toxicokinetic parameters were rounded to 3 significant figures; • t max are given with one decimal; • ratios are given with 2 significant figures; • CV% are given as integer. DEVIATIONS The following deviations were observed: • Some samples (TK time-points 2, 4 and 8 hours for 160 and 480 mg/kg/day dose groups) were diluted 4-fold prior being analyzed. These samples were below the limit of quantitation multiplied by the dilution factor (thus 2 µg/mL instead of 0.5 µg/mL) for 25-desacetyl rifapentine. It was agreed with the study director not to re-assay these samples undiluted for 25-desacetyl rifapentine and they were thus reported as <2µg/mL. • 31 toxicokinetic blood collection times were different by more than 15% from the theoretical times described in the study plan. The actual collection times were used for these samples for toxicokinetic analysis. These deviations are not considered to have hindered the quality of the study. Toxicokinetic parameters Individual toxicokinetic parameters for rifapentine in macaque plasma are given in Section 10.2 in Table 7 . In males, exposure increased infra-dose proportionally on Day 1 and remained almost constant on Day 29. After administered dose was increased from 160 to 480 mg/kg/day (3-fold increase in the dose), in females, exposure increased infra-dose proportionally on Days 1 and 29. Accumulation ratios AUC 0-24 on Day 29 versus Day 1 ratios descriptive statistics are summarized in Table 4 and fully described in Table 6 . Mean geometric ratios were significantly below 1 thus indicating a decrease of exposure upon repeated dose, probably due to an auto-induction phenomenon. For the highest dose, 480 mg/kg/day, the AUC 0-24 Day 29 versus Day 1 ratios were higher consistent with a lower decrease of exposure after repeated dose. Concentrations of rifapentine and 25-desacetyl rifapentine were below the lower limit of quantitation (LLOQ, 0.5 µg/mL for both) in all control animals. Whatever the sex, the dose and the toxicokinetic sampling day, rifapentine concentrations were above the LLOQ up to 24 hours in all treated animals. Plasma concentrations of the rifapentine metabolite, 25-desacetyl rifapentine, were all below 0.5 µg/mL or below 2 µg/mL for samples diluted 4-fold. Overall, considering AUC 0-24 ratios between males and females, no obvious sex effect was observed. Rifapentine AUC 0-24 decreased after repeated dose administration indicating a possible autoinduction phenomenon. The exposure decrease after repeated administration was quite similar at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day (about 50 %). For the high dose (480 mg/kg/dose) the decrease was lower (below 40%). After administered dose was increased from 80 to 160 mg/kg/day (2-fold increase), in females, the exposure remained almost constant on Day 1 and Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infradose proportionality on Day 1 and remained almost constant on Day 29. After administered dose was increased from 160 to 480 mg/kg/day (3-fold increase), in females, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and on Day 29. In males, exposure increased with infra-dose proportionality on Day 1 and dose proportionality on Day 29. Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 371 371/700 ABBREVIATIONS GALT: Gut-associated lymphoid tissue H&E: Hematoxylin & eosin, Hematoxylin and eosin MALT: Mucosal-associated lymphoid tissue PAS: Periodic acid-Schiff SER: Smooth endoplasmic reticulum STS: Semi-thin section TEM: Transmission electron microscopy UTS: Ultra-thin section TITLE: M000473 -Rifapentine -4-week subchronic oral toxicity study in macaques with a 2-week recovery period ANATOMIC PATHOLOGIST: Bernar det Details concerning the study design are documented in the Material and Methods section of the Toxicology Study Report, particularly the macaques source, age, sex, number, and allocation to the different groups, as well as details of organ weighing, and of the macroscopic, microscopic and transmission electron microscopic examinations performed. For convenience, "rifapentine" has been used instead of "M000473-Rifapentine", throughout the Anatomic Pathology Phase Report. On completion of the four-week oral administration of rifapentine to macaques, at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, including a 2-week recovery period at 480 mg/kg/day, rifapentine-related findings were noted in the liver, adrenals, digestive, lymphoid system and kidneys. In the liver, the main findings consisted in slightly to moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights, minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement, and minimal to moderate hypertrophy of hepatocytes from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in both sexes, with slight dose-related effects on weights for males and in both sexes for the other findings. The hypertrophy of hepatocytes concerned centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes in all cases, but also periportal hepatocytes, at lower occurrence and severity degree. In most cases, centrilobular and midzonal hypertrophy was more prominent in subcapsular lobules, where it was associated, at minimal to mild degrees, with large multinucleated syncytial hepatocytes and multifocal subcapsular necrosis (with/without hemorrhage and/or acute/subacute inflammation), from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, in both sexes and with slight dose-related effects. These findings were considered to most likely result from liver enzyme induction, with possible roles of (i) relative hypoxia, when considering the increased severity noted in subcapsular lobules, (ii) drug class effect and/or increased total bilirubin plasma levels, when considering the syncytial hepatocytes. A slight increase in hepatocytic neutral fat contents was also noted from 80 and 160 mg/kg/day upwards, in males and females respectively, slightly dose-related in males. This finding was considered as a most likely adaptative finding, possibly linked with decreases in total cholesterol plasma levels. Finally, a minimal/mild light pale discoloration was noted in one male and one female at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids, and to the increase in neutral fat contents. Anatomic Pathology Phase Report M000473 (Rifapentine) -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 6 Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 373 373/700 Transmission electron microscopic (TEM) examination, performed in 480 mg/kg/day-treated monkeys killed at the end of the dosing period, confirmed the microscopic findings, and showed that the hepatocyte hypertrophy was due to an increase in smooth endoplasmic reticulum (SER), consistent with liver enzyme induction. At 480 mg/kg/day, light pale discoloration, increased weight, hypertrophy of centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes, syncytial hepatocytes, foci of necrosis, and increase in neutral fat contents did not fully reverse. In the adrenals, minimal to moderate hypertrophy of zona fasciculata cells, with more or less correlative decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia, was noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 80 and 480 mg/kg/day, these findings correlated with slightly higher absolute and/or relative weights and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in some macaques. In the absence of any stress-related findings in the study, these findings were considered as a most likely adaptative response, possibly linked to the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels. At 480 mg/kg/day, the increase in weight, and the decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia of zona fasciculata cells had almost fully reversed. In the digestive tube, a minimal increase in incidence or severity of lacteal duct distension was noted in the ileum from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. At 480 mg/kg/day, this finding was associated with minimal to moderate lacteal duct ending cysts, filled with neutral fat, in the duodenum or jejunum from all males and one female, and with minimal increase in macrophagic infiltration of jejunal and ileal villi in one male (with increase in cytoplasmic eosinophilia). A possible link of these findings with the decrease in total cholesterol plasma levels may be evoked. Minimal/mild dark or orange discoloration of the stomachal, duodenal, jejunal, ileal and/or cecal mucosa was also noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, with relation to dose but without relation to sex, and was attributed to the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids. At 480 mg/kg/day, dark or orange discoloration did not fully reverse, and the lacteal duct endings cysts did not reverse, in addition, morphologically similar cysts were noted in the mesenteric lymph nodes sinuses of one female. In spleen and lymph nodes, a mild to moderate increase in lymphoid follicles hyperplasia was noted from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. In the spleen the finding correlated with slightly higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, dose-related in males, and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in one female at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day. This finding was attributed to a stimulating effect on lymphoid follicles, ie, on the immune system B cell compartment. At 480 mg/kg/day, the increase in follicular hyperplasia did not fully reverse in lymph nodes. Anatomic Pathology Phase Report M000473 (Rifapentine) -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 7 Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 374 374/700 In kidneys, light pale discoloration was noted in one female at 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids. This finding was still noted in one female at the end of the recovery period. In addition minor findings were noted, the final attribution of which to rifapentine remains questionable. Some may have participated to a more generalized effect on the lymphoid system: hyperplastic lymphoid follicle in the thymus from one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, and slightly higher incidence and/or severity of (i) multifocal lymphoid lymphocytic infiltration in the sublingual and lacrymal glands and prostate (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), mandibular gland (from 160 mg/kg/day), and ciliary body (at 480 mg/kg/day), (ii) multifocal and most likely inflammatory lymphocytic infiltration in stomachal neural plexuses (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and (iii) multifocal perivascular/vascular chronic inflammation in brain (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), epididymis, skeletal muscle and sciatic nerve (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and testis and cervix (at 480 mg/kg/day). At the end of the recovery period (480 mg/kg/day), only the increase in multifocal lymphocytic infiltration was still noted in neural plexuses and lacrymal gland. The other questionable findings were of poor biological (and toxicological) relevance: minimal macrovacuolation of zona reticularis cells in the adrenals from one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, focal adrenocortical hemorrhage in one macaque at 480 mg/kg/day, and non steatotic vacuolation of renal proximal tubular cells in one macaque at 480 mg/kg/day. Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 ANATOMIC PATHOLOGIST Bernard Remandet signed electronically DVM, Diplomate ECVP Preclinical Safety Disposition, Safety Montpellier Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 376 376/700 MATERIAL AND METHODS Details concerning the study design are documented in the Material and Methods section of the Toxicology Study Report, particularly the macaques source, age, sex, number, and allocation to the different groups, as well as details of organ weighing, and of the macroscopic, microscopic and transmission electron microscopic examinations performed. All study plan-defined tissues from all macaques killed at the end of the dosing and recovery periods were evaluated by light microscopy. In addition to the routine hematoxylin and eosin (H&E), periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) and Oil red O stains were performed on liver sections from all macaques (Oil Red O stain was performed on liver frozen section). PAS stain was used to determine the glycogenic contents of the hepatocytes, indirectly estimated by their cytoplasmic clearness on H&E stained section. Oil Red O stain was used to determine the neutral fat contents of the hepatocytes, based on the vacuolation of periportal hepatocytes seen on the H&E stained sections in 18M, 19M, 20F (Group 3 -160 mg/kg/day), 27M, 28F and 31F (Group 4 -480 mg/kg/day). Oil red O stain was also performed on kidney frozen section of 26M (Group 4 -480 mg/kg/day), to further characterize the vacuolation noted in renal proximal tubular cells, and on jejunum frozen section of 25M and 29F (480 mg/kg/day), to further characterize the lacteal duct ending cyst contents. The few organs that were not weighed or were noted missing, damaged or incomplete during macroscopic and microscopic examinations are recorded in individual data sheets ( ~xr1i ) and in ~xr2i for organs not weighed. This was considered to have no impact on the study validity and conclusions, and, particularly, the fact that the pituitary of 3M (control Group 1, killed at the end of the dosing period) was not weighed, with subsequent absence of statistical analysis for that organ, because of only two valid weights in control males. Since the liver functions were modified (see the Toxicology Study Report), and since of weight, macroscopic and light microscopic rifapentine-related findings (see the Anatomic Pathology Phase Report Sections 6. 1, 6.2, and 6.3) , the examination of the liver samples, taken at the end of the dosing period in all control and 480 mg/kg/day-treated macaques for possible TEM examination, was performed. Because of only minimal/mild light pale discoloration of the kidneys of a single 480 mg/kg/day-treated female (Section 6.2), without clinical pathology, weight and microscopic correlates (see the Toxicology Study Report, and the Anatomic Pathology Phase Report Sections 6.1 and 6.3), the examination of the kidney samples, taken for the same purpose, was not performed. DATA COLLECTION AND ANALYSIS SYSTEMS Data were recorded directly using PathData version 6 software. ORGAN WEIGHTS Absolute and relative group mean organ weights are presented in ~xr3i , individual organ weights are presented from ~xr4i to ~xr5i . Rifapentin-related findings noted at the end of the dosing period were as follows: Liver: slightly higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in both sexes, with statistically significant differences when compared with controls in all treated male groups and at 160 mg/kg/day in females (relative weight only). A dose-related effect was only noted in males, with moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights at 480 mg/kg/day. When compared with the highest individual control values, all males and two to three females had higher absolute and relative liver weights in all rifapentine-treated groups. Macroscopic, light microscopy and TEM correlates consisted in organ enlargment, hepatocellular hypertrophy, and increase in SER, respectively (Sections 6.2, 6.3 and 6.4). Spleen: slightly higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in both sexes, with statistically significant differences when compared with controls for males at 480 mg/kg/day only. A dose-related effect was only noted in males, with moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights at 480 mg/kg/day. When compared with the highest individual control values, two to three males and one to two females had higher absolute and/or relative spleen weights in all Rifapentine-treated groups. Macroscopic and microscopic correlates consisted in organ enlargment and lymphoid follicles hyperplasia, respectively (Sections 6.2 and 6.3). Adrenals: slightly higher absolute and/or relative weights in one male and two females at 80 and 480 mg/kg/day, when compared with the highest individual control values, not related to dose, and without mean group variation. There was a macroscopic correlate in one male at 480 mg/kg/day (Section 6.2), and microscopic correlate consisted in cortical cells acidophilia and hyperplasia (Section 6.3). At the end of the 2-week recovery period (480 mg/kg/day), liver and adrenals weight variations did not fully reverse, since one male had still slightly higher absolute liver and adrenals weights. Spleen weight variations had fully reverse. These findings are summarized in Text Table 1 . Rifapentin-related and possible Rifapentin-related findings were as follows: Liver End of the dosing period • hypertrophy of hepatocytes in all Rifapentin-treated macaques, minimal to moderate in centrilobular and midzonal areas (all cases) and minimal to mild in periportal areas (most cases), with slightly higher severity degree at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day. In subcapsular lobules, hypertrophy of centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes was more prominent in almost all macaques, with the same slightly higher severity degree at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day. In that location and in both sexes, hypertrophy was associated with: -minimal or small number of large multinucleated hepatocytes (syncytial hepatocytes resulting most likely from the fusion of hypertrophic hepatocytes and displaying frequently a preserved trabecular shape): from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, with slightly higher severity degree at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, -minimal or mild multifocal subcapsular necrosis (of single or small group) of hepatocytes, with/without hemorrhage and/or acute/subacute inflammation: from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, with slightly higher severity degree at 480 mg/kg/day, • slight increase in the hepatocytic neutral fat contents (evidenced by Oil Red O stain on liver frozen section): from 80 and 160 mg/kg/day upwards, in males and females, respectively, with slightly higher severity degree in males at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day (on H&E stained section, the corresponding vacuolation of periportal hepatocytes was visible in a few macaques, see Section 3). These findings were attributed to rifapentine. Hepatocyte hypertrophy was considered to most likely result from liver enzyme induction, known to occur in human (1) . TEM examination showed this finding was due to an increase in SER, consistent with liver enzyme induction (Section 6.4). However, because hypertrophy was more prominent in subcapsular lobules, the relative hypoxia noted in that zone may have played a role, as suggested by the foci of necrosis, only present in that zone (with the syncytial hepatocytes). In addition, a class effect may be evoked for the induction of the syncytial hepatocytes, known to occur following rifabutin dosing in the rat (2). The higher total bilirubin plasma levels noted in rifapentine-treated macaques (see the Toxicology Study Report) may also have played a role, since syncytial hepatocytes are a consistent pathological finding in idiopathic human neonatal/infant liver cholestasis (3). These findings were as follows: End of the dosing period • Thymus: single hyperplastic lymphoid follicle in thymus medulla from one female at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, • Mandibular, sublingual and lacrymal glands, eye ciliary body and prostate: slightly higher incidence and/or severity of multifocal periductal lymphocytic infiltration in sublingual, mandibular and lacrymal glands, and of multifocal lymphocytic infiltration in ciliary body and prostate: from 80, 160 and at 480 mg/kg/day for (i) sublingual gland, lacrymal glands and prostate, (ii) mandibular gland, and (iii) ciliary body, respectively. • Other organs: slightly higher incidence and/or severity of multifocal lymphocytic infiltration in neural plexuses from cardia or pylorus, and of multifocal perivascular/vascular chronic inflammation in several organs, including testis, epididymis, cervix, skeletal muscle, sciatic nerve and brain: from 80, 160 and at 480 mg/kg/day for (i) brain, (ii) neural plexus, epididymis, skeletal muscle and sciatic nerve, and (iii) testis and cervix. The findings noted in thymus, mandibular, sublingual and lacrymal glands, eye ciliary body and prostate may be fortuitous, as they are known to occur at a low incidence and/or severity degrees in controls. However, because they were relative the lymphoid compartment of these organs, they may have contributed to the expression of a more generalized stimulating effect of rifapentine on the lymphoid system. The findings noted in the other organs may also have participated to that effect, although a same direct link cannot be established, because of their most likely (neural plexus) or pure (testis, epididymis, cervix, skeletal muscle, sciatic nerve and brain) inflammatory nature. End of the 2-week recovery period (480 mg/kg/day): these findings had fully reverse, except for the multifocal periductal lymphocytic infiltration in lacrymal glands and lymphocytic infiltration in neural plexuses, still noted in males. multifocal subepithelial and perivascular lymphocytic infiltration in the urinary bladder, exocervix and vaginal mucosae, only noted (exocervix and vagina) or noted with slightly higher occurrence and severity degrees (urinary bladder) in rifapentine-treated macaques killed at the end of the dosing period, but noted with similar occurrence and severity degrees in controls killed at the end of the recovery period, • congenital anomalies: minimal or mild, uni or bilateral, ora serrata cyts in the eyes of several monkeys, including controls; and hypogenetic tubules in the renal cortex of 29F er (480 mg/kg/day), • traumatic pathology: focal, multifocal or zonal skeletal muscle degeneration/necrosis (with hemorrhagic and granulomatous infiltration) or fibrosis (with/without myocyte atrophy, hemorrhagic or siderophagic infiltration) in several macaques, including controls, attributed to the antiparasitic treatment performed during the quarantine period, Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 393 393/700 ELECTRON MICROSCOPY Only the liver of all control and 480 mg/kg/day-treated macaques killed at the end of the dosing period was examined by TEM (Section 3). Group results are presented in ~xr12i , individual results in ~xr13i . Rifapentine-related findings noted on semi-thin (STS) and ultra-thin (UTS) sections were as follows: • moderate increase in the amount of SER (UTS), with correlative mild increase in the hepatocytic size (STS & UTS), • mild increase in greenish (STS) or lipidic (UTS) vacuoles accumulation, with progressive shift from microvacuoles, micro-and mediovacuoles, to micro-to-macrovacuoles, • single multinucleated hepatocyte (UTS) in one female. This examination confirmed the hepatocytic hypertrophy, multinucleated hepatocytes and increase in neutral fat contents (Section 6.3), and showed the hepatocytic hypertrophy was due to an increase in SER, compatible with liver enzyme induction (4). Besides, a few findings were noted, of little biological significance and the final attribution of which to rifapentine remains questionable: mild accumulation of more or less large singlemembrane bound saccules (filled with granular, most likely proteidic, material) in 27M ed , focal subcapsular neutrophilic infiltration in 30F ed (possibly corresponding to focal acute inflammation associated to necrosis noted on H&E stained sections), and minimal distension of bile canaliculi, with minimal bile accumulation, in 31F ed .
