The other findings, noted on semi-thin and/or ultra-thin sections, were attributed to physiological variations (variable glycogen contents and of Ito cells green or lipidic vacuolation), or to spontaneous pathology (minimal or mild lipofuscins accumulation in most macaques, and focal chronic inflammation in 31M ed ). Anatomic Pathology Phase Report M000473 (Rifapentine) -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 28 Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 395 CONCLUSION On completion of the four-week oral administration of rifapentine to macaques, at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, including a 2-week recovery period at 480 mg/kg/day, the following main organ weights, macroscopic, microscopic and TEM findings were noted: Liver • minimal/mild light pale discoloration in one male and one female at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids, and to the increase in neutral fat contents (see below), • slightly to moderately higher absolute and relative mean weights, minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement, and minimal to moderate hypertrophy of hepatocytes from 80 mg/kg/day upwards in both sexes, with slight dose-related effects on weights for males and in both sexes for the other findings. The hypertrophy of hepatocytes concerned centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes in all cases, but also periportal hepatocytes, at lower occurrence and severity degree. In most cases, centrilobular and midzonal hypertrophy was more prominent in subcapsular lobules, where it was associated, at minimal or mild degrees, with large multinucleated syncytial hepatocytes and multifocal subcapsular necrosis (with/without hemorrhage and/or acute/subacute inflammation), from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, in both sexes and with slight dose-related effects, • slight increase in hepatocytic neutral fat contents, from 80 and 160 mg/kg/day upwards, in males and females respectively, with slight dose-related effect in males. TEM examination, performed at 480 mg/kg/day, confirmed the microscopic findings and showed that the hepatocyte hypertrophy was due to an increase in SER, consistent with liver enzyme induction. At 480 mg/kg/day, the light pale discoloration, increased weight, hypertrophy of centrilobular and midzonal hepatocytes, syncytial hepatocytes, foci of necrosis, and increase in neutral fat contents did not fully reverse. Adrenals: minimal to moderate hypertrophy of zona fasciculata cells, with more or less correlative decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia, from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose and sex-related effects. At 80 and 480 mg/kg/day, these findings correlated with slightly higher absolute and/or relative weights and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in some macaques. At 480 mg/kg/day, increase in weight, and decrease in microvacuolation and increase in cytoplasmic acidophilia of zona fasciculata cells had almost fully reversed. Anatomic Pathology Phase Report M000473 (Rifapentine) -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 29 Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 396 396/700 Digestive tube • minimal/mild dark or orange discoloration of the stomachal, duodenal, jejunal, ileal and/or cecal mucosa from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, dose-related but not sex-related, and attributed to the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids, • minimal increase in incidence or severity of lacteal duct distension in the ileum from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects, • minimal to moderate lacteal duct ending cysts, filled with neutral fat, in the duodenum or jenunum of all males and one female at 480 mg/kg/day, • minimal increase in macrophagic infiltration of jejunal and ileal villi in one male at 480 mg/kg/day, with increase in cytoplasmic eosinophilia. At 480 mg/kg/day, dark or orange discoloration did not fully reverse, and the lacteal duct endings cysts did not reverse, in addition, morphologically similar cysts were noted in the mesenteric lymph nodes sinuses of one female. Spleen and lymph nodes: mild to moderate increase in lymphoid follicles hyperplasia from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, without dose-and sex-related effects. In the spleen, the finding correlated with slightly higher absolute and relative mean weights from 80 mg/kg/day upwards, dose-related in males, and with minimal/mild macroscopic enlargement in one female at 80 and 160 mg/kg/day. At 480 mg/kg/day, increase in follicular hyperplasia did not fully reverse in lymph nodes. Kidneys: light pale discoloration in one female at 480 mg/kg/day, possibly due to altered color, resulting from the ability of rifapentine to color body tissues or fluids. This finding was still noted in one female at the end of the recovery period. In addition, minor findings were noted, the final attribution of which to rifapentine remains questionable. Some may have participated to a more generalized effect on the lymphoid system: hyperplastic lymphoid follicle in the thymus of one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, and slightly higher incidence and/or severity of (i) multifocal lymphoid lymphocytic infiltration in the sublingual and lacrymal glands and prostate (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), mandibular gland (from 160 mg/kg/day), and ciliary body (at 480 mg/kg/day), (ii) multifocal and most likely inflammatory lymphocytic infiltration in stomachal neural plexuses (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), and (iii) multifocal perivascular/vascular chronic inflammation in brain (from 80 mg/kg/day upwards), epididymis, skeletal muscle and sciatic nerve (from 160 mg/kg/day upwards), testis and cervix (at 480 mg/kg/day). At the end of the recovery period (480 mg/kg/day), only the increase in multifocal lymphocytic infiltration was still noted in neural plexuses and lacrymal gland. The other findings were questionable and of poor biological (and toxicological) relevance: minimal macrovacuolation of zona reticularis cells in the adrenals from one macaque at 160 and 480 mg/kg/day, focal adrenocortical hemorrhage in one macaque at 480 mg/kg/day, and non steatotic vacuolation of renal proximal tubular cells in one macaque at 480 mg/kg/day. The people who actually sign the study report are summarized on the automatically created signature page. The aim of this study phase was to investigate the effects of rifapentine on the regulation of various Cyp isoforms (expressed as the expression level of investigated gene, relative to control conditions) in monkey liver following a 4-week repeated oral gavage of rifapentine at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day (Toxicology Study TSA1482). LIST OF TABLES LIST OF FIGURES EXPERIMENTAL PROCEDURE Details concerning the study design are documented in the Toxicology Study Report. Only the information relevant to this study phase is presented hereafter. CYP MRNA QUANTIFICATION Disruption and homogenization of animal tissues A piece of approximately 25 mg of each frozen liver was placed into the appropriate volume of Buffer RLT-β-Mercaptoethanol 1%, disrupted and homogenized using the Mixer Mill MM300 according to the manufacturer's instructions (Qiagen®). The tissue lysates were used in total RNA extraction and purification subsequent steps. RNA EXTRACTION AND QUANTIFICATION Expression levels of mRNA for cyp1a1, cyp2a24, cyp2e1, cyp3a5 and cyp3a8 were evaluated by RT-PCR using the following protocol: • Total RNA preparation -Total RNA extraction and purification were performed using RNeasy mini Kit according to the manufacturer's instructions (Qiagen®), using Qiacube robot. -Retro-transcription of total RNA and Real-Time Polymerase Chain Reaction (RT-PCR) were performed in two steps, using the High Capacity cDNA Archive Kit (Applied Biosystems®) for reverse transcription step and the TaqMan Fast Universal PCR Master Mix according to the manufacturer's instructions (Applied Biosystems®). Amplification and detection were performed in a final volume of 20 µL, and contained 300 nM forward primer, 300 nM reverse primer and 200 nM TaqMan probe. These reactions were performed on an ABI PRISM 7500 Fast Sequence Detector System from Applied Biosystems. Typical time profiles for these studies are 95°C, 20 sec; 40 cycles 95°C, 3 sec; 60°C, 30 sec. Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 685 685/700 Enzyme Induction Phase Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 7 • cyp1a1 Probe -TaqMan gene Expression assay Rh03043069_m1 • cyp2a24 Probe -TaqMan gene Expression assay Rh02790084_mH • cyp2e1 Probe -TaqMan gene Expression assay Rh02790474_m1 • cyp3a5 Probe -TaqMan gene Expression assay Rh02788714_m1 • cyp3a8 Probe -forward primer: 5' CTGGCCACTCACCCTGATGT 3' -reverse primer: 5' ATAGGTGGGTGGTGCCTTATTG 3' -TaqMan Probe: 5' ACTGCAGGAGGAAAT 3' Housekeeping gene: the expression level of the various mRNA were normalised relative to a reference housekeeping gene, ie, mRNA 18s. • 18s Probe -TaqMan Ribosomal RNA control reagent. DETERMINATION OF INDUCING EFFECTS All results are expressed as the expression level of each gene investigated in the livers of rifapentine-treated female monkeys (0, 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day for 4 weeks) versus vehicletreated female monkeys on one hand and of rifapentine-treated male monkeys (0, 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day for 4 weeks) versus vehicle-treated male monkeys on the other hand (all obtained from study TSA1482 (Animal Group 2, Group 3 and Group 4 versus Group 1, respectively). A "female/male" ratio was analyzed at each tested dose (0, 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day for 4 weeks) and for each cyp investigated. CALCULATIONS Both, the gene of interest and the housekeeping gene (18s) amounts (Ct), were determined in the same monkey liver sample. Therefore, for data obtained from the same sample, the measured amount of the gene of interest was normalized to the amount obtained for the housekeeping gene in that sample (∆Ct). Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 686 686/700 Enzyme Induction Phase Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 8 The amount of the gene of interest, normalized to the housekeeping gene, in rifapentine-treated monkey liver samples, was then compared (∆∆Ct) to a calibrator (mean of vehicle-treated monkey liver samples). Since, in the conditions we used, the efficiency of the PCR was close to one, the final result given for the gene of interest in rifapentine-treated monkey liver samples, relative to the calibrator (ie, vehicle-treated group, with a mean fold-induction arbitrarily fixed to 1 for all studied genes), was determined by evaluating the expression level (fold induction) (2 -∆∆Ct ). Ct: threshold cycle (the PCR cycle at which an increase in reporter fluorescence above a baseline signal can first be detected). ∆Ct = Ct gene of interest -Ct 18s : the difference in threshold cycles for the gene of interest and the housekeeping gene. ∆∆Ct = ∆Ct treated tissues -∆Ct calibrator : the difference in threshold cycles normalized for rifapentinetreated monkey liver samples versus calibrator. 2 -∆∆Ct : the fold induction of the gene of interest in rifapentine-treated monkey liver samples relative to the calibrator. The fold induction value (2 -∆∆Ct ) for each replicate of the monkey liver sample is reported in Table 1 and Table 2 . Then a geometrical mean of the fold induction values was determined for each animal treatment group. Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 687 687/700 Enzyme Induction Phase Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 9 RESULTS CYP MRNA EXPRESSION IN MONKEY LIVER Cyp mRNA expression ratings in monkey liver have been arbitrary established as follows: -Mean expression level ≤ 2-fold the calibrator = no or only a very weak non-biologically significant increase -2-fold the calibrator < Mean expression level ≤ 3-fold the calibrator = weak increase -3-fold the calibrator < Mean expression level ≤ 5-fold the calibrator = intermediary increase -5-fold the calibrator ≤ Mean expression level = high increase In males The mRNA measurements performed in the livers of male monkeys treated with rifapentine at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day for 4 weeks versus male monkeys receiving the vehicle only for 4 weeks, showed (see Table 1 and Figure 1 ) that rifapentine produced: • For cyp1a1 gene, no or only very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. For two animals, ie, 11M (80 mg/kg/day) and 27M (480 mg/kg/day), individual fold increases of cyp1a1 were in the ranking of weak increase (3.0-and 2.8-fold, respectively). • For cyp2a24 gene, a weak mean increase at the highest dose in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. For two animals, ie, 18M (160 mg/kg/day) and 27M (480 mg/kg/day), individual fold increases of cyp2a24 were in the ranking of weak (2.3-fold) and high (5.4-fold) increases, respectively. • For cyp2e1 gene, no or only very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. • For cyp3a5 gene, a weak mean increase at the three doses in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. For four animals, ie, 11M (80 mg/kg/day), 17M and 18M (160 mg/kg/day) and 25M (480 mg/kg/day), individual fold increases of cyp3a5 were in the ranking of intermediary (4.0-, 3.2-, 3.5-and 4.3-fold, respectively) increases. • For cyp3a8 gene, intermediary (low and mid doses) and high (top dose) mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. For one animal, ie, 27M (480 mg/kg/day), a 26.8-fold increase of cyp3a5 was observed. Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 688 688/700 Enzyme Induction Phase Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 10 In females The mRNA measurements performed in the livers of female monkeys treated with rifapentine at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day for 4 weeks versus female monkeys receiving the vehicle only for 4 weeks, showed (see Table 2 and Figure 2 ) that rifapentine produced: • For cyp1a1 gene, no or only very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. • For cyp2a24 gene, weak (low and mid doses) and intermediary (top dose) mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. • For cyp2e1 gene, no or only very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. • For cyp3a5 gene, weak (low and mid doses) and intermediary (top dose) mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. For three animals, ie, 21F (160 mg/kg/day) and 30F and 31F (480 mg/kg/day), individual fold increases of cyp3a5 were in the ranking of intermediary (3.2-, 4.1-and 4.1-fold, respectively) increases. • For cyp3a8 gene, weak (mid dose) and intermediary (low and top doses) mean increases in the expression levels in rifapentine-treated monkeys compared to vehicle-treated monkeys. For one animal, ie, 31F (480 mg/kg/day), a 6.9-fold increase of cyp3a8 was observed. Toxicology Study Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 694 694/700 Enzyme Induction Phase Report M000473 -Rifapentine -TSA1482 Property of the Sanofi group -strictly confidential Page 16 CONCLUSION The aim of this study phase was to investigate the effects of rifapentine on the regulation of various cyp isoforms (expressed as the expression level of investigated gene, relative to the control (vehicle-treated animals) in monkey livers following a 4-week repeated oral gavage of rifapentine to Macaca fascicularis at 80, 160 and 480 mg/kg/day (Toxicology Study TSA1482). The mRNA measurements performed in monkey livers are reported in Table 1 and Table 2 and illustrated in Figure 1 and Figure 2 . Whatever the gender, rifapentine produced: • no or only a very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels of cyp1a1 genes; • no or only a very weak non-biologically significant mean increases in the expression levels of cyp2e1 genes; • a weak (males) to intermediary (top dose in females) mean increases in the expression levels of cyp2a24; • a weak (all doses in males) to intermediary (top dose in females) mean increase in the expression levels of cyp3a5; • a high (top dose in males) to intermediary (low and top doses in females) mean increases in the expression levels of cyp3a8. Most "female/male" mRNA expression increases ratio did not suggest any major gender differences in the effect of rifapentine on cyp mRNA expression in monkeys.
